caption: Extensive museum with an extraordinary collection of minerals/stone/gems. You can spend hours there too see all.  We have visited many mineralogy museums around the world.  This is absolutely the best!!!

If you're interested in rocks, diamonds, minerals, jewelry, gems, and any other strange crystalline natural formations, this is the place to satisfy you. The museum is cut out of the Jardin du Luxembourg, and features an incredible collection of specimens from around the world... And also outer space. No kidding, I touched a piece of rock from Mars! The entry also features a nice gallery of paintings of important natural landscapes around France.

Collection : 5/5  Excellent. Thousands of gems, crystals, and stones spanning 12 rooms.  Service: 3/5 Good. The ticket vendor was minimally warm. Very transactional.  Ambience: 5/5 Excellent. Imagine an old 19th century curio cabinet expanded into rooms!  Cleanliness: 5/5 Excellent. Spotless, without dust. Extremely well maintained.  Value: 5/5 Excellent. 6€ for full admission. Cash only.  Overall: 4.6/5 Excellent. I intend to suggest this museum to friends and family who are visiting.
This museum was on my bucket list for years and didn’t disappoint in any way. The cases are filled with such a unique collection of old and new pieces. A must see for any mineral historian.
Admission was 6 euros for 2 people. Nothing was in English, the pamphlet had information in English but that was only in a few pages. Only the signs “Do not touch” was big and in English.
A perfect place for precious stones lovers! There is a wide rage of collections in the world. The entry price is only 6 euro and it’s located juste next to the famous Luxembourg garden.

I really recommend to visit this little museum if you're interested in geology. They have so much minerals to see. Furthermore, theses are presented in old, beautiful, well lighted showcases. And the building has so much charme!
An extensive collection in several beautiful rooms. The aisles are a bit narrow, but still accessible. The pamphlets are well-made and informative. Recommended for people interested in minerals
Really cool place for those who like rocks. The collection is incredible and they have some very interesting rocks that I've never seen before

The mineralogical collection of MINES ParisTech, preserved at the historic Vendôme Hotel for over two hundred years, is recognized as one of the most complete and spectacular mineralogical collections in the world. Today, it is comprised of around 100,000 samples, including 4,000 on exhibit, and over 2,900 species of minerals!
A lot of World's minerals collected different time, different places, different conditions. Worth any money... Exactly 6 Euro

This little museum was easy to find and get into - so although it's very specialized, it's quite accessible to normal tourists. I don't know much about rocks, but there was much to enjoy here, you can tell that the exhibits are world class.
Nice museum to visit, plenty of minerals, gorgeous and amazing
Inside the enginiering school you will find an amazing muzeum. One of the 3 muzeums, like Louvre that has some royal jewels.
Wonderful little museum. One of the richest in the world. Friendly staff ready to comment on minerals and gems if you ask them.
Very interesting museum, more of a family museum.
Beautiful and unique treasure. 1 of the best in paris and the 4th worldwide
Nice Muzeum located inside the university Mines Paris

Probably the best museum in Paris (yes, even better than the Louvre in many respects). I took over 200 photos.. so many that my phone became too hot to hold and my battery dropped precipitously. There are many many rooms and every room has incredible mineral samples - some huge, some colorful, in fantastic shapes.
It says open till 17:00 but the doors close at 16:00. The entry guards knew and didn’t care to update Google or help in any way.
This place is known for its huge collection of minerals. The staff is friendly and well knowledged about the artifacts kept.

They don't take credit cards. Cash only. The year is 2023 in the world busiest tourist city. What? Couldn't even get in.  Also the guy asking for the admission fee was just some random dude in plain clothes. Held his hand out and asked for 3 euros. I'm not sure if he was a bum or actually worked there.
Absolutely the greatest mineral specimens I have ever seen!

Truly an impressive mineral collection with beautiful specimens, divided into small room and each room has a few family of minerals. They don't have many rocks yet, a few metamorphic and basic magmatic rocks. They also have a nice range of meteor debris.
Great museum, people were very friendly. You can see some cool stuff in there
Great place to visit with kids!
There are so many minerals and gems.
Incredible specimens on display.
Very nice collection ! Worth it for kids who are interested in rocks and minerals
Lovely place to visit and learn.
For gem and rock lovers. Use Google translate to help with understanding of you cannot read French
